    {
      "question": "Two poles of height $6 \\text{ m}$ and $11 \\text{ m}$ stand on a plane ground. If the distance between their feet is $12 \\text{ m}$, find the distance between their tops.",
      "answer": "$13 \\text{ m}$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Represent the poles as vertical segments on a horizontal ground.",
          "Form a right-angled triangle by drawing a line parallel to the ground from the top of the shorter pole.",
          "Use the Pythagorean theorem to calculate the hypotenuse."
        ],
        "derivation": "$\\text{Let } AB = 6 \\text{ m and } CD = 11 \\text{ m be the poles.} \\\\ \\text{Distance between feet } AC = 12 \\text{ m.} \\\\ \\text{Draw } BE \\perp CD \\text{ such that } CE = AB = 6 \\text{ m.} \\\\ DE = CD - CE = 11 - 6 = 5 \\text{ m.} \\\\ \\text{In right } \\triangle BED, BD^2 = BE^2 + DE^2 \\\\ BD^2 = 12^2 + 5^2 = 144 + 25 = 169 \\\\ BD = \\sqrt{169} = 13 \\text{ m}$"
      },
